C LBfd
(* Leaky-Semicolon LBfd worked example (Jeffrey, Riely, Batty, Cooksey, Kang, *)
(* Vafeiadis, "The Leaky Semicolon", POPL 2022). Load-buffering with a FALSE *)
(* (linear-arithmetic) data dep: the store writes a+1-a, which is the constant *)
(* 1 for every value of a. The syntactic store mentions the read, but the *)
(* written value does not vary with it. *)
(* *)
(* The adjacency-based idiom folder in dependsReally cannot see a-a inside *)
(* a+1-a (the terms are not adjacent). The linear-arithmetic normalization *)
(* pass computes a's net coefficient (1 - 1 = 0) and classifies both data *)
(* deps isSemantic=false. Before that pass the deps were mis-classified real. *)
(* *)
(* evalConst(a+1-a) = 0+1-0 = 1, so the program writes carry the constant 1 *)
(* and the wired candidate is the LB cycle r0=r1=1 — structurally identical to *)
(* LB-real.litmus (real dep r+1) and LB-fake-xor-cycle.litmus (fake dep *)
(* r^r^1). Only isSemantic differs: WEAKEST FORBIDS the real LB-real cycle *)
(* (UNSAT via jfCoherence) but ALLOWS this one (SAT), because the fake dep is *)
(* excluded from sdep so jfCoherence sees no cycle in sdep u jf. *)
{ }
 P0                        | P1                        ;
 r0 = READ_ONCE(*x)        | r1 = READ_ONCE(*y)        ;
 WRITE_ONCE(*y, r0+1-r0)   | WRITE_ONCE(*x, r1+1-r1)   ;
exists (0:r0=1 /\ 1:r1=1)
